# Linter Errors Are NEVER Acceptable

Every linter error and warning MUST be fixed. No exceptions.

## Rules

1. After ANY edit, run ReadLints on every file you touched.
2. If there are errors or warnings, FIX THEM before doing anything else.
3. NEVER tell the user linter errors are "false positives", "pre-existing", "expected", "safe to ignore", or "known issues".
4. NEVER dismiss PSScriptAnalyzer warnings about unused variables. If the linter says a variable is unused, restructure the code so the linter is satisfied.
5. NEVER dismiss PowerShell parse errors about missing braces or keywords. If the linter reports a structural error, the code structure must be changed until the error is gone.
6. If you cannot figure out how to fix a linter error, tell the user honestly. Do NOT hand-wave it away.
7. Do NOT proceed to the next task, respond to the user, or consider your work done while linter errors exist in files you edited.
8. Treat every linter error with the same urgency as a runtime crash.
